Preamble
This license permits use of the Concept Principle (as defined below) subject to the attribution and responsible-use requirements set out in this document. The license is provided without warranty. This license governs the use of the expression and documented formulations of the Concept Principle; it does not by itself create rights in abstract ideas beyond what applicable law provides.

0. Definition of Scope
This license does not claim ownership over the innalienable right to pursue happiness. That right is universal, pre-existing, and not subject to exclusive control.

The intellectual property covered under this license consists solely of:
    1. The restored and logically complete definition of the innalienable right to pursue happiness, defined as the mutual, non-exploitative condition in which one’s pursuit of happiness must not prevent another person from pursuing theirs; and
    2. The conceptual application of that restored definition, including its use as:
        • a civilizational security protocol,
        • a governing kernel for artificial intelligence systems,
        • a philosophical foundation for human coordination,
        • and any explanatory frameworks, diagrams, formulations, examples, or implementations authored by Branton Allan Baker.

These contributions are collectively referred to as the Concept Principle.

Definitions
For purposes of this Credibility License, the following terms have the meanings set out below.

- "Concept Principle"
  - The conceptual application for realized function originated by Branton Allan Baker, including its formulations, explanations, diagrams, examples, source or object implementations, and any fixed expression of the foregoing as disclosed by the author in any medium. The Concept Principle includes, but is not limited to, the following conceptual elements:
    - "Core Directive" (defined below);
    - the "innalienable right to pursue happiness as security protocol" (defined below);
    - the definition of "innalienable" as written herein (see definition below).
  - Inclusion of the foregoing elements does not limit the Concept Principle to those elements alone; other related formulations, manifestations, or implementations disclosed by the author are part of the Concept Principle.

- "Core Directive"
  - A foundational instruction, principle, or rule that governs or guides the intended operation, behavior, or deployment of the Concept Principle. The Core Directive may be expressed as an algorithmic rule, design constraint, normative statement, or operational requirement forming the conceptual core of the Concept Principle.

- "innalienable right to pursue happiness as security protocol"
  - A conceptual formulation that treats the individual's right to pursue happiness as a design or security parameter to be preserved and protected by implementations of the Concept Principle. As a protocol concept, it may influence threat models, access controls, data-handling practices, decision criteria, or other security-related behaviors in systems that implement the Concept Principle.

- "innalienable"
  - For purposes of this Credibility License, "innalienable" (also sometimes spelled "inalienable") means inherent and not legitimately transferable, waivable, or extinguishable by external actors. In the context of the Concept Principle, it denotes rights or conditions the author intends implementations to respect and preserve as core constraints or normative requirements. This definition is declarative of author intent; its legal effect depends on applicable law and any binding contract accepting this license.

- "Recipient"
  - Any person or organization that receives, accesses, uses, reproduces, modifies, publishes, distributes, sublicenses, sells, or otherwise makes use of the Concept Principle or any Derivative Work.

- "Derivative Work"
  - A work that is based upon, derived from, or incorporates the Concept Principle or any substantial portion of a fixed expression of the Concept Principle, whether in Source Form or Binary Form, including translations, adaptations, modifications, or other transformations that would, under applicable law, be treated as derivative works of the covered expression.

- "Use"
  - To exercise any of the rights granted by this license, including but not limited to copying, modifying, reproducing, distributing, publicly performing or displaying, sublicensing, selling, deploying, or otherwise exploiting the Concept Principle or any Derivative Work.

- "Distribution"
  - Any act by which a Recipient makes the Concept Principle or a Derivative Work available to third parties, including publication, upload, release, sale, transfer, or distribution in any format, whether in Source Form or Binary Form.

- "Source Form"
